<section class="intro-section mb-12">
  <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
  <p>
    <strong>Web Policy</strong> standardizes <strong>declarative domain policy</strong> &mdash; the rules
    that decide whether an <em>action</em> is permitted, an entity qualifies, or an approval is required.
    &ldquo;Orders over $50k need a second sign-off,&rdquo; &ldquo;a minor cannot consent,&rdquo; &ldquo;a
    policy can't bind without an underwriter review&rdquo;: each is a business rule, and today every app
    re-encodes them as scattered <code>if</code>-branches that no auditor can read and no product can
    govern.
  </p>
  <p>
    Web Policy fixes the <strong>rule meta-schema</strong> &mdash; how a rule is <em>expressed</em>,
    <em>versioned</em>, and <em>scoped</em> &mdash; by adopting the OMG <strong>DMN</strong> vocabulary
    (decision tables + FEEL-style expressions). It standardizes the meta-schema, <em>not</em> the rule list
    (the same doctrine as the intents). The rule engine, the tamper-evident proof, and the enforcement seam
    are the slices that build on top; this project is the declarative vocabulary they share.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #4338ca; font-size: 1rem;">Not validation, not the engine</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      <a href="/projects/webvalidation/">Web Validation</a> owns input <em>invalidity</em> &mdash; a field
      is wrong. Web Policy owns whether an <em>action</em> is allowed &mdash; a different concern, so it
      earns its own home rather than extending validation (separate-and-decouple). And it is not the
      <em>engine</em>: the proof-of-compliance machinery (hash-chained signed decision log) and the OPA
      PDP/PEP enforcement split are the <a href="/backlog/093-business-rule-manager-proof-of-compliance/">#093</a>
      Forks 2&ndash;3 that compose <em>on</em> this meta-schema. Web Policy composes
      <a href="/projects/webexpressions/">Web Expressions</a>, <a href="/projects/webcontexts/">Web
      Contexts</a>, Web Validation, and <a href="/projects/webtraces/">Web Traces</a> &mdash; it does not
      absorb them.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

